          "body": "The word hinneh (behold) in 3:12 signals that what follows is the theological engine of the entire arrangement. God does not merely assign the Levites administratively; He claims them as His own because He has already claimed Israel's firstborn as His own — and the Levites stand in their place. The claim originates on a specific night: 'on the day that I struck down all the firstborn in the land of Egypt, I sanctified to Myself all the firstborn in Israel' (3:13). This is not abstract theology. God's act of redemption created a corresponding claim of ownership. Because the Passover blood shielded Israel's firstborn while Egypt's died, those firstborn belong to Him. The Levites are God's solution to that ongoing ownership claim: instead of requiring every Israelite family to devote its firstborn son to tabernacle service, God takes an entire tribe as a corporate substitute. The Levitical order is the Passover institutionalized."
