          "title": "The arithmetic of substitution — 273 left over (3:39-51)",
          "body": "The chapter's climax is a counting problem with a theological answer. Moses counts the Levites: 22,000. He counts Israel's firstborn males: 22,273. The near-equivalence is striking — God engineered the substitution so that the numbers would be close — but the 273-person surplus is real and must be resolved (3:46). Each of the 273 who lacks a Levitical substitute must be redeemed individually at five shekels by the sanctuary standard (3:47). The total — 1,365 shekels of silver (3:50) — goes to Aaron and his sons (3:48, 51). The chapter closes with Moses executing the transaction exactly as commanded (3:51). The precision is theologically deliberate: the substitution is real, not symbolic. Every firstborn has either a Levite or a ransom payment standing in his place. No one remains unredeemed within the covenant community. This prefigures the New Testament's own arithmetic: the ransom paid for those for whom no substitute exists is not silver but blood (1 Peter 1:18-19; cf. Mark 10:45)."
